defaultS
defaultummary default&#xa0;defaultIt is my belief that an undesirabledefault provider drivendefault whiplash industry has developed in this country that defrauds the insurance industry and that the vast majority of such claims are exaggerated or contriveddefault, and that the current adversarial legal system is an inappropriate tool for assessing damagesdefault.
default&#xa0;
defaultI have had extensive experience in the management and treatment of spinal, including neck injury, both within and outwith
default 
defaultthe medico legal context. I have written many hundreds of medical reports for both claimant and defendant in personal injury litigation.
default&#xa0;
defaultI am well informed on the
default 
defaultlarge body of medical evidence on
default 
defaultthe subject, and in passing would recommend any party interested in this subject to Malleson’s scholarly book “Whiplash and other useful Illnesses.” McGill Press.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe clinical problemdefault&#xa0;defaultAlthough a high speed rear end impact can cause severe, and occasionally fatal injury the vast majority of  whiplash claims are the result of lesser and frequently trivial impacts.
default&#xa0;
defaultOn impact the occupant’s 
defaulthead is first jerked backwards 
defaultand rebounds off the head restraint. Extreme hyperextension of the neck which prompted the first use (
defaultUSA
default 1938) of the term “
defaultwhiplash” does not now occur because of universal head restraints. 
default&#xa0;
default It is very rare in whiplash cases for there to be any truly objective signs of injury. X rays are usually taken defensively if the patient attends hospital and rarely show any abnormality 
default&#xa0;
defaultI shall use the term 
defaultPUWC (Prolonged Unconfirmable Whiplash Complaints)default in the following discussion into which category the vast majority of whiplash claimants fall.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe injury is best regarded as a sprain of the neck which is expected to give rise to some pain and stiffness for a few weeks like sprains elsewhere in the body (eg sprained ankle) and then return to normal.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe usual claimant however continues with complaints months or years after recovery is expected,  Such persistence of symptoms are often ratified and encouraged by persons whose income depends on offering treatment eg physiotherapists, osteopaths, and the transcription of symptoms into documents and case notes often gives a spurious ratification to symptoms.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the assessment of injury therefore no reliance should be placed on the observations of anyone with a pecuniary interest in the case.
default&#xa0;
defaultEarly access to physiotherapy (the rehabilitation code) has compounded the problem appearing to ratify injury before the presence or absence of injury has been assessed. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThedefault Claimdefault Problemdefault&#xa0;
defaultIn recent years following similar process in the 
defaultUSA
default the number of whiplash cases seeking compensation has risen alarmingly for the following reasons. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultDiagnosisdefault&#xa0;
defaultGenuine significant neck injury
default for example fracture or dislocation or both
default presents 
defaultno
default difficulty in diagnosis
default. Without such damage the injury is a ligament or muscle strain and spontaneous recovery is expected within a matter of weeks.
default&#xa0;
defaultFinding a investigation (scan
default,
default 
defaultx ray or blood test) to confirm whiplash in the hope of distinguishing the genuine from the fraudulent is a forlorn hope, certainly with current technology.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe fraudulent is easily identified by the perceptive expert, but persons with a pecuniary interest in management or an expert with ambitions to expand their practice will not do so.
default&#xa0;
defaultAmong the features which I have found consistent in the fraudulent claimant are
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
